Dissection of venom glands: Female adult wasps, after wetting and sterilisation for 20 seconds in 70% ethanol, were held in a PBS solution in a watch glass and the ovipositor pulled from the rear of the abdomen using fine forceps under a stereomicroscope. The venom gland, venom reservoir and ovaries remained attached to the ovipositor and they could then be identified. The venom gland was removed using fine forceps and placed immediately in 30 microliters of Trizol (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA). The venom gland reservoir was also removed and immediately placed in 5 microliters of 4x NuPAGE LDS sample buffer (Invitrogen). In order to preserve the integrity of the samples any dissection which took longer than 2 minutes from the time of ovipositor removal until the gland or reservoir were in the appropriate buffer was abandoned.
RNA extraction: To prepare RNA between 30 and 40 dissected glands were placed in 30 microliters of Trizol and processed according to the manufacturers instructions (Sigma) in a small sterile 0.6 ml polypropylene Eppendorf tube. Sterile glycogen, as suggested by the manufacturer, was added at the final ethanol precipitation step to ensure that the very small amounts of purified RNA were precipitated and could be collected by centrifugation. The RNA from the extraction was dissolved and stored in sterile, DEPC treated, distilled water at -70 degrees C.
Pyroseqencing: The DNA used for sequencing was 6 micrograms amplified cDNA derived from venom RNA prepared from M. aethiopoides venom glands dissected and purified as described above. The SMART cDNA preparation protocol (Clonetech) was followed according to the manufacturers instructions using 3 microliters of RNA solution as starting material and 26 cycles of amplification. To obtain the quantity of cDNA required for sequencing (6 micrograms) the cDNA protocol was repeated three times and the amplification products were pooled.

GM12878 is a lymphoblastoid cell line produced from the blood of a female donor with northern and western European ancestry by EBV transformation. It was one of the original HapMap cell lines and has been selected by the International HapMap Project for deep sequencing using the Solexa/Illumina platform. This cell line has a relatively normal karyotype and grows well. Choice of this cell line offers potential synergy with the International HapMap Project and genetic variation studies. It represents the mesoderm cell lineage. Cells will be obtained from the Coriell Institute for Medical Research [coriell.org] (Catalog ID GM12878).

HepG2 is a cell line derived from a male patient with liver carcinoma. It is a model system for metabolism disorders and much data on transcriptional regulation have been generated using this cell line. It grows well, is transfectable, and represents the endoderm lineage. Cells will be obtained from the America Type Culture Collection (ATCC) [atcc.org] (ATCC Number HB-8065).

K562 is an immortalized cell line produced from a female patient with chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML). It is a widely used model for cell biology, biochemistry, and erythropoiesis. It grows well, is transfectable, and represents the mesoderm linage. Cells will be obtained from the America Type Culture Collection (ATCC) [atcc.org] (ATCC Number CCL-243).

Description.Title: Generic sample from Burkholderia multivorans CGD1

Comment.Paragraph: Burkholderia CGD1 was isolated from a lung biopsy of a CGD (chronic granulomatous disease) patient. CGD1 induces a high proinflammatory response in infected cells in vitro and has the highest ability to attach and enter cells than any other isolate of BCC studied so far (e.g. ~70% cells infected by CGD1 versus ~8% cells infected by the environmental isolate ATCC 17616). The CGD1 isolate killed mice at least 3 times more efficiently and also much faster than ATCC 17616.

Description.Title: Generic sample from Burkholderia multivorans CGD2

Comment.Paragraph: CGD2 was isolated from blood of a CGD (chronic granulomatous disease) patient. This strain is unique in that it produces copious amounts of exopolysaccharides (EPS) that endows the bacteria with a mucoid phenotype. CGD2 attaches and enters cells at a low rate (comparable to ATCC 17616) however it induces a poor proinflammatory response in infected cells (induces the lowest levels of TNF alpha of any other strain studied). Interestingly, the CGD2 isolate killed mice at least 3 times more efficiently and faster than ATCC 17616.

Description.Title: Generic sample from Burkholderia multivorans CGD2M

Comment.Paragraph: Burkholderia CGD2M is a spontaneous mutant of CGD2 that lacks the mucoid appearance of its parent strain, CGD2. Interestingly, CGD2M induces a higher proinflammatory response and a higher entrance into cells in vitro than its parent strain, CGD2.
